rope as a special envoy to work with Robert Livingston in negotiating the dispute with France. Jefferson proposes a "bargain" that will result in the acquisition of the Louisiana Territory. In a confidential message to Congress, Jefferson seeks $2,500 to send a small party of men to explore the Missouri River. Congress concurs, and Jefferson's secretary Meriwether Lewis will lead the expedition. Settling the boundaries with Native American lands is a major theme of the volume. In reality, "settling" results in major cessions of Indian lands to the American government. During the months of this volume Jefferson never leaves the capital, even for a brief sojourn at Monticello. He does, however, enjoy a visit of six weeks from his daughters and two of his grandchildren. They participate in Washington society, capture the affection of Margaret Bayard Smith, and brighten Jefferson's days.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvArchives. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAaron Burr.  aAct of Congress.  aAlbert Gallatin.  aAlexander Wolcott.  aAmerican Antiquarian Society.  aAmerican National Biography.  aAmerican Revolution.  aAmerican frontier.  aArthur St. Clair.  aBattle of Germantown.  aBattle of Tippecanoe.  aBenedict Arnold.  aBenjamin Hawkins.  aBenjamin Henry Latrobe.  aBritish Agent.  aCaptain general.  aCession.  aCharles Willson Peale.  aCitizens (Spanish political party).  aCitizenship of the United States.  aCommissioner.  aConsideration.  aContinental Congress.  aDaniel Carroll.  aDavid Meriwether (Kentucky).  aDeWitt Clinton.  aDistrict attorney.  aDry dock.  aExcellency.  aFederal Union.  aFort Adams.  aFrederick the Great.  aFrigate.  a